```suggestion
# q-expansions of modular forms
```
This is just a random suggestion, if you have any knowledge of a typographic standard that says `q` should be capitalized here just ignore this comment.

The only "typographic standard" in the written literature is to be consistently inconsistent (e.g. the way Springer have mangled [this famous paper of Katz](https://link.springer.com/chapter/10.1007/978-3-540-37802-0_3)). I'll go for lowercase.

```suggestion
def cuspFunction : ℂ → ℂ := _root_.cuspFunction n (f ∘ ofComplex)
```
Personally I think this is more readable, but as you prefer. (Similarly below)

while we are here, do we want something like 

```
lemma mdifferentiable_iff {f : ℍ → ℂ} {τ : ℍ} :
    MDifferentiable 𝓘(ℂ) 𝓘(ℂ) f  ↔ DifferentiableOn ℂ (f ∘ ofComplex) {z : ℂ | 0 < z.im} := by ..
```

Since MDifferentiable is what shows up in the modular form definition, so this would be a nice way to get the condition directly?

I'm not sure this would be so helpful, because the `DifferentiableOn` doesn't mean "`f` is differentiable at every point of `s`" but "`f` is differentiable within `s` at every point of `s`". If `s` is open these conditions are equivalent but one needs to invoke a lemma to show this, which kind of cancels out the usability gain. 

It's a pity we don't have a direct way of asserting "f is differentiable at every point of `s`", analogous to `AnalyticOnNhds`.

The indents look strange here.

```suggestion
theorem exp_decay_atImInfty [NeZero n] [CuspFormClass F Γ(n) k] :
    f =O[atImInfty] fun τ ↦ Real.exp (-2 * π * τ.im / n) := by
  simpa only [neg_mul, comp_def, ofComplex_apply, coe_im] using
    (exp_decay_of_zero_at_inf (mod_cast (Nat.pos_iff_ne_zero.mpr (NeZero.ne _)))
          (periodic_comp_ofComplex n f)
          (eventually_of_mem (preimage_mem_comap (Ioi_mem_atTop 0))
            (fun _ ↦ differentiableAt_comp_ofComplex f))
          (zero_at_infty_comp_ofComplex f)).comp_tendsto
      tendsto_coe_atImInfty
```
the _root_. makes me wonder if we want the cuspFuntion in the root namespace. Could it maybe go into a periodic namespace? or something similar?
Yes, I think that's a good idea, I'll put it in `Function.Periodic`.
